            <!-- Explanatory content -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this aircraft performance calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is inspired by FAA
                <em>Pilot’s Handbook of Aeronautical Knowledge</em> Chapter 11
                and typical POH performance charts. It uses a simplified
                mathematical model to show how
                <strong
                  >weight, density altitude, wind, runway slope and
                  surface</strong
                >
                affect takeoff, climb, cruise and landing.
              </p>
              <p>
                It is designed for
                <strong
                  >student pilots, instructors and aviation enthusiasts</strong
                >
                who want to build intuition about aircraft performance, not to
                replace certified performance data.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Density altitude model</h3>
              <p>
                First we estimate <strong>pressure altitude</strong> from field
                elevation and altimeter setting, then apply a temperature
                correction to get <strong>density altitude</strong>.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Pressure altitude</strong> (ft):</p>
                <p>PA ≈ Field Elevation + (29.92 − QNH) × 1000</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>ISA temperature</strong> at elevation (°C):
                </p>
                <p>
                  T<sub>ISA</sub> ≈ 15 − 2&nbsp;°C per 1000 ft × (Field
                  Elevation / 1000)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Density altitude</strong> (ft):</p>
                <p>DA ≈ PA + 120 × (OAT − T<sub>ISA</sub>)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is the same rule-of-thumb used in many training materials:
                about <strong>120 ft of DA per °C</strong> above ISA.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Weight effect on distance and climb</h3>
              <p>
                Takeoff and landing distance vary approximately with the
                <strong>square of weight ratio</strong>, while climb rate varies
                roughly with the <strong>inverse of weight</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Weight ratio: r<sub>W</sub> = W / W<sub>ref</sub></p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Distance scaling</strong> (takeoff &amp; landing):
                </p>
                <p>D ≈ D<sub>ref</sub> × r<sub>W</sub><sup>2</sup></p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Climb rate scaling</strong>:</p>
                <p>ROC ≈ ROC<sub>ref</sub> × (1 / r<sub>W</sub>)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Density altitude effect on distance and climb</h3>
              <p>
                Higher density altitude reduces engine power and lift,
                increasing distance and reducing climb. We use simple linear
                correction factors referenced to sea level:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>Altitude factor (distance):</p>
                <p>f<sub>DA,dist</sub> ≈ 1 + 0.1 × (DA / 1000)</p>
                <p class="mt-2">Altitude factor (climb):</p>
                <p>f<sub>DA,ROC</sub> ≈ max(0, 1 − 0.1 × (DA / 1000))</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                So at 5,000 ft density altitude, distances increase by roughly
                50%, and climb rate is reduced by about 50% from the reference
                value.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Wind, slope and surface corrections</h3>
              <p>
                We apply additional multiplicative factors similar to those used
                in training:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Headwind / tailwind:</strong> about −10% distance per
                  10 kt headwind, +10% per 2 kt tailwind.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Runway slope:</strong> about +10% distance per 1%
                  uphill, −10% per 1% downhill.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Surface:</strong> selectable factor (1.0 paved, 1.15
                  short grass, 1.3 wet grass/soft field).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>5. Cruise TAS and fuel burn</h3>
              <p>
                For cruise, we start from a reference TAS and fuel flow at a
                given altitude and assume:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  TAS increases slightly with altitude (thinner air, same power)
                  up to a point.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Fuel flow is mostly a function of power setting, so we keep it
                  near constant for small altitude changes.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  Altitude ratio: r<sub>h</sub> = (Cruise Altitude − 6000) /
                  1000
                </p>
                <p>TAS ≈ TAS<sub>ref</sub> × (1 + 0.01 × r<sub>h</sub>)</p>
                <p>
                  Fuel flow ≈ FuelFlow<sub>ref</sub> (constant in this simple
                  model)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">Trip time (h) ≈ Distance / Groundspeed</p>
                <p>Fuel required (gal) ≈ Trip time × Fuel flow</p>
              </div>

              <h2>Limitations and safe use</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is a <strong>generic model</strong>, not tied to any
                  specific aircraft type or certification basis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It ignores effects like propeller efficiency, mixture setting,
                  runway contamination, obstacles, and performance margins.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It assumes
                  <strong>proper short-field and climb techniques</strong> are
                  flown accurately.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-red-600 font-semibold">
                Never use this calculator as the sole source for go/no-go
                decisions. Always consult your aircraft’s POH/AFM and applicable
                regulations.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical training ideas</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Compare performance at sea level vs. a high-elevation airport
                  on a hot day.
                </li>
                <li>
                  See how a 10% increase in weight affects takeoff distance and
                  climb rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Experiment with headwind vs. tailwind to visualize why
                  tailwind takeoffs/landings are discouraged.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Estimate trip time and fuel for different cruise altitudes and
                  winds.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

